               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300916-321-person2635">
                  SARAH 
                  ION
               <interp inst="t18300916-321-person2635" type="surname" value="ION"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300916-321-person2635" type="given" value="SARAH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300916-321-person2635" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the daughter of John Ion. on the 31st of August I was going along <placeName id="t18300916-321-crimeloc1651">Old-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18300916-321-crimeloc1651" type="placeName" value="Old-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18300916-321-crimeloc1651" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300916-321-off1649 t18300916-321-crimeloc1651"></join>; the prisoner <rs id="t18300916-321-deflabel1652" type="occupation">sells fruit</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300916-321-defend2632 t18300916-321-deflabel1652"></join> there, and I gave him half a crown in mistake for a half-penny, for some plums - I dropped it in his basket; I found it out in two minutes, and went back- he said he had not got it, and had not half a crown about him; he said the officer might search him if he chose, which he did, but could not find it in his pockets - he then took off his hat, and found it there.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. PHILLIPS. Q. Who gave you the half-crown? A. My sister; I did not look at the money as I gave it him - I had 7s. 9 1/2d. in my hand; the prisoner had plums in his basket - I did not see it drop in; the plums very likely covered it - I did not state that I gave it him - I threw it; I have said I did not think the prisoner had any idea of stealing it - the officer made me prosecute here to-day; the Magistrate sent a warrant - I was unwilling to prosecute - the officer did not scold me; he said it was his duty to take him when he found the half-crown upon him after his denying it.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300916-321-person2636">
                  WILLIAM 
                  ROBERTS
               <interp inst="t18300916-321-person2636" type="surname" value="ROBERTS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300916-321-person2636" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300916-321-person2636" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the officer. This girl applied to me - I went up to the prisoner; she was entreating him to return her the half-crown which she had given in place of a half-penny - I said, "If you have the half-crown, return it back;" he said he had no half-crown in his possession - he then turned out his pockets, and said,"If you doubt my word, search me;" I searched his<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183009160140"></xptr>pockets, but found nothing - I took off his hat, and the half-crown fell down; I said, "I must take you into custody;" he begged hard, and said if I would let him go he would do so no more - I said I must do my duty to the public.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I did not know the half-crown was there; I had sold all my fruit but 1d. worth.</p>
               <p>GUILTY. Aged 18.</p>
               <p>
